  "text": "An in-plane fracture is represented by an array of n infinitely long dislocations. When modeling multiple ruptures, it is useful to add a seismic radiation term to the stress balance equation (as in [CITATION_1] . The radiation damping term is representative of the outflow of energy due to seismic waves, and it's incorporation ensures that the slip rate remain finite at all times. For the modeling of the localization stage, on the other hand, both quasi-dynamic and quasi-static approaches are appropriate. In Section 3, we wish to compare the dimensions of the localization patch with predicted dimensions for quasi-static crack, therefore we adopt a quasi-static approach. In Section 4, on the other hand, we model multiple cycles and therefore use a quasi-dynamic approach. We write the stress balance equation as: where the subscripts are dislocation indexes, σ is the normal stress, τ 0 is a constant,τ ∞ is the remote stressing rate, g ij is an elasto-static kernel, δ is the slip, G is the shear modulus, β is the shear wave speed, and δ QD is set to be equal to 1 when taking a quasi-dynamic approach, and is set to 0 otherwise. The state on i evolves as:",
